    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "but if the \"historical tradition\" part is so \"debatable\" and \"subjective\" like you said, doesn't that basically mean the originalist method is broken? it seems like if a method can be used to justify literally anything just by picking certain history books, then it's not actually a reliable legal standard anymore. isn't it more accurate to say they're using it as a shield for activism rather than a real way to interpret the law?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are hitting on a core criticism of originalism: if the historical record is ambiguous, the methodology becomes inherently pliable. Critics argue that this flexibility allows justices to cherry-pick precedents that support a desired outcome, effectively using \"history\" as a post-hoc rationalization for their policy preferences. From this viewpoint, the method functions less as a rigid interpretive tool and more as a sophisticated rhetorical shield for judicial policymaking. Therefore, many scholars view the current application as leaning heavily toward activism disguised in historical language.",
      "source": "target",
